@Ninja Of The Rift In a sense yes, you can just write typescript then you type a command which converts the typescript into javascript.

But actually just use Angular and it will automatically take care of that for you, that's basically what angular does. 

You write in typescript and it is already setup to  convert to javascript for you.

@Ninja Of The Rift You can, typescript is a tool to be used with javascript.

Think of it this way, you have a car with a parking warning system, if you are reversing to close to something it warns you, javascript is the car, typescript is the warning system.

So are the end of the day either way you are using javascript, but typescript will just let you know early that the javascript you are writing might cause problems, it's an add on to javascript you could say and not really a new programming language.

@Vs Sm Standard packages for common tasks, if you install react you only get maybe state management then you have to decide what else to install, with angular you get:
forms, pwa, testing, web components, animations, i18n and more from just installing the angular package.

For me what I love is that Angular was built from the ground up in typescript, when I use other frameworks the typescript configuration feels like an afterthought.
